Today we have the honor of wishing our co-founder, @paulnicklen, a very happy birthday! To celebrate Paul and his infectious passion for conservation is simple, but to express his immeasurable impact on our organization and its mission is impossible.

Each day, as we work to amplify our ocean‚Äôs stories and restore its health, we do so with Paul‚Äôs reliable voice and commitment to change, helping to steer the ship. While not all have the opportunity to encounter Paul‚Äôs prowess for leadership firsthand, his unreplicable ability to capture and create resonant stories can be experienced much more broadly. Fearlessly exploring every corner of the world, he brings unreachable scenes vividly and candidly to our fingertips, opening the door to worlds that may otherwise go unseen. Paul engages us with charismatic creatures and their realities. His love for the ocean and its wildlife radiates through his work, and, with his artistic voice, proximity becomes negligible, and action is inspired. 

Share in the celebration, and help Paul and our team continue to bring our ocean‚Äôs stories to life by signing up for the Tide. Together, we can echo our ocean‚Äôs voice and work toward a rich, biodiverse future for our planet. // Link in Bio

3 reasons why I love working with silhouettes and you should too!

Emotional Resonance:
Silhouettes paint with emotions, casting a spell of drama and mystery. The strong contrast between darkness and light breathes life into my creations, conveying intense feelings that linger in the viewer‚Äôs soul.

Sculpting with Shadows:
In the world of silhouettes, details fade away, leaving room for the dance of form and composition. As an artist, I revel in the opportunity to sculpt with shadows, experimenting with angles, framing, and negative space to weave a visual tapestry that captivates the observer.

Universal Poetry:
Silhouettes are my universal language. They transcend genres and settings, allowing me to tell stories through shapes. From the quiet grace of a solitary tree to the silhouette of a cat, each frame is a canvas for my emotions, a testament to the versatility and timeless allure of this artistic expression.

‚ÄúI know I‚Äôm a handful baby‚Äù, part of the new series ‚ÄúRelationship status:‚Äù, where we (@wheresaddie and @aialahernando) use self portraiture as a means of translating/exploring the private as public female experience. 
The artists use site specific real floral arrangements, alongside contemporary artifacts within the artists‚Äô lived experiences; the personal objects strewn across the works serve both as a portrait of the modern women but also of the artists themselves, to create a feeling of longing in the work- to see what is concealed, to understand who is attached. This form of active looking implicates the viewer into the process and highlights further into the series, the role of desire as a (un)productive force.

These are ESSENTIAL to succeed in the workplace üíªüíØüìàüë©üèº‚Äçüíº
-
1Ô∏è‚É£ Be willing to give everything a go üôãüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è- if you haven‚Äôt done it before or unsure, don‚Äôt be scared to ask for help! Tell your supervisor that you‚Äôll give it your best shot, but may need to be supervised or taught. 

A ‚Äúcan-do‚Äù attitude and an eagerness to learn is one of the best qualities to have. I constantly remind myself that I grow the most when I‚Äôm pushed out of my comfort zone, so the feeling of discomfort is actually something that I need to embrace. 

NOTE: this only refers to things that are inside the scope of your role & will help you develop. Be more cautious about saying yes to ‚Äúbusy work‚Äù just because your supervisor doesn‚Äôt want to do it.
.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Close the Loop üîÅ- at the end of every meeting or conversation, report back what you understood as actions you need to do & by when. Then, as you complete those actions, report back to inform the person they are done & any other information that might be useful (eg if doing research, what the main findings were. If reaching out to someone, what their response was).

Similarly, if you need help with something/are stuck, or there is something blocking your progress, let them know too (eg ‚Äúthe contact is away on leave and will be back Monday, which is when I will follow up again‚Äù).

Don‚Äôt wait for them to have to chase you to figure out that the task has been done or has been held up.

Closing the loop helps build trust. It lets your supervisor know that you are reliable and they can delegate important tasks to you.

I started doing 10 slow reps throughout the day. I made a rule: every time I passed the same wall in my house, I would do 10 reps. Or when I was waiting for food to cook in the kitchen etc. It maybe ended up being 4-6 times in the day (so ~50 reps every day). 

It didn‚Äôt really affect the flow of my day too much BUT it completely eradicated my shoulder pain! üò± Not to mention, my ‚Äòwinging‚Äô shoulder blades that I have battled with all my life, are slowly finding a better position sitting FLAT onto my back (at last!!! ü•∫ü•∞)

üëâüèº I CAN NOT RECOMMEND THESE ENOUGH. üëàüèº

Especially if you suffer from any upper thoracic pain, neck pain, back pain, poor shoulder movement, or struggle with bad posture.

‚è∞ As always, daily consistency will get you the best and quickest results. I still do these, but they are now a quick part of my warm up before any workout. It maybe takes 2 min to do 3 slow sets üëäüèº

Product development is long and often frustrating. When you watch my videos, you see the sketch then you see the final result in a matter of 60 seconds but the truth is often my designs take anywhere between a year to sometimes 3 years to go from concept to real thing. 

Why?

It all begins with finding the right fabric for what I‚Äôm trying to achieve. If I‚Äôm lucky, I may already have a fabric I love that I‚Äôve used before that I wanna use again! But often the fabric sourcing bit itself can take months.

The sampling process can take anywhere from a few months minimum to almost a year, sometimes more! During this time, fabric can change, design may change, the perfect fit will always be obsessed over, and I‚Äôll sample over and over and over again until it feels just right. I‚Äôll won‚Äôt stop until it feels ready, and I‚Äôm happy.

Then there‚Äôs the actual production which includes the weaving of the fabric, the dying of the fabric, the cutting of the pattern pieces, the careful sewing of the garment etc etc‚Ä¶

Good things just take time.

Lots of üö¢ questions, here are my top 10 tips! Feel free to add to the list if you‚Äôve been on a cruise.

3. Book the unlimited spa first day (more than just treatments, full haven of rest & rejuvenation).
4. Don‚Äôt peak on the first night (took a full day in the sauna to recover)
5. Room service is free (I found out on the last day).
6. Seasoned cruisers can be savage (especially at the buffet). 
7. Wifi is not free (just get the premium package)
8. Payment is all in USD.
9. Bring seasickness tablets and take them before you get sick. 
10. Plan your days as much as you can before you board!

Spotting a pangolin in the wild is rare. In all our years documenting wildlife, often spending weeks embedded in the bush, we've only seen a handful of these elusive mammals in the wild. They're often more active at night, shuffling through the undergrowth in search of termites, ants and larvae, which they dig out of nests and burrows using their impressive claws. Once they've carved an opening in the dirt, a long sticky tongue goes to work sucking up insects en masse. ‚Å£
‚Å£
They are profoundly unique animals. But they are also under threat. All eight species of pangolins found throughout the world are threatened by the illegal wildlife trade and populations are rapidly declining. Despite their shy nature, they remain one of the most trafficked mammals in the world and are illegally trapped in their thousands to feed a growing demand for their scales and meat. Without strict regulations and enforcement, these remarkable animals may be pushed to extinction. This #WorldPangolinDay, let's join forces and pledge to never let that happen.‚Å£
‚Å£‚Å£

Made it to Venice, Italy yesterday with only enough time to see sunset and then find a place to eat dinner. But it didn‚Äôt really matter because any amount of time in Venezia always thrills me to my core. And what a sunset we saw!! üòç

I am sad to report that crowd level seems to be back to pre-pandemic levels and for myself I think this will be my last time here unless it‚Äôs in the dead of winter when there are likely to be less tourists (?) as being part of over-tourism for a place nearly being loved to death, doesn‚Äôt feel really good. I need to do more research and talk to more people that live here before I make any final decisions. 

What are your thoughts on over-tourism or visiting Venice? 

The city is seeking to combat over-tourism with a tax for day trippers and other tourists that I‚Äôve outlined on my blog. I personally think it‚Äôs a good move. And I will be curious to see what residents like my friend @neumarc think as it gets implemented and we see whether or not it has a positive impact. 

Venice also banned large cruise ships from the Venetian Lagoon as it caused intense damage to the ecosystem when they were allowed. Speaking of cruises, I‚Äôm in Italy to head to the port and fishing town of Chiaggio where we are joining @vikingcruises for their ‚ÄúEmpires of the Mediterranean‚Äù sailing. It is Dante‚Äôs first time on a cruise and Viking is one of the only lines I will go on an ocean cruise with because their ship has a passenger capacity less then 1/3 the size of the average for the industry. They also seem to be making honest strides to ensure they operate in ways that are as responsible and ethical as possible. I‚Äôve also never met an employee who didn‚Äôt LOVE working for Viking. The ones I‚Äôve met when on the river and one ocean cruise so far have been some of the happiest tourism employees I‚Äôve found the world over.

This is starting to sound like a commercial üòÇ and I didn‚Äôt mean to do that. But I am grateful to be hosted by Viking again so I can share more about them. AMA in the comments and I‚Äôll answer honestly ‚§µÔ∏è

Thank you for making it this far. I hope your week is off to a great start ‚ù§Ô∏è

And then there is this woman, my mother. Today is Mother‚Äôs Day in Norway, a date I only remember because my sister reminds me, but I somehow always remember the date for it here in England. But no matter the date, this woman needs to be celebrated. She‚Äôs simply my heart, my beating heart, and hearing her say it will all be well, is all the assurance I need to keep going when times are hard. She so incredibly warm you simply cannot sit next to her without feeling uplifted. Her wisdom has carried me through everything life has to offer, and now to see my daughter lean on her for comfort, for love, for consistency in friendship, and for stability, when her young life is facing more challenges her age should need to carry on her shoulders, is so beautiful to watch. My mother brings joy and laughter that is infectious, and she has this beautiful way of laughing at herself which brightens any room she enters. I know I‚Äôm lucky, but I also know it‚Äôs hard work, because every time I tell her about people who comment on how lucky I am to have her, she smiles and simply tells me it‚Äôs a choice she makes every morning when she gets up, to be the best she can be, and it‚Äôs work, it‚Äôs a consistent choice. I try to mirror her ability to love during hardship and to never give up. And when I fall asleep at night next to my wonderful little girl, I count myself lucky to have them both in my life, and do my best in becoming for my daughter, what my mother is to me, a rock of love to lean on and to unwaveringly be encouraged to reach any goal and dream I may have. In this week‚Äôs newsletter I wrote about portraiture with direct light, and used a series shot with my mother as an example. You can read it via a link in my profile to ‚ÄúThe Photography Workshop‚Äù newsletter. All previous newsletters are archived there, and you can access them all should you miss it on the day they are sent out. I hope you‚Äôll enjoy it! Happy Norwegian Mother‚Äôs Day to all of you. xx

From playful antics to tender moments, elephants flow with emotion. While the calves at Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) have traumatic pasts, the love and companionship of the other elephants and the dedicated keepers help them grow and heal. 

Each calf has a different personality but they all share affection and deep trust for each other and their caretakers. This is often expressed through holding trunks, nuzzling, and leaning, or, in more goofy moments, a tackle in a mud hole, bumping into each other, and swinging their trunks.

Learn more about elephants at Reteti and how to support their conservation at the link in bio. Photo by @amivitale. @vital.impacts #elephants #conservation #kenya #elephantlove @nikonusa @nikonambassador

Mr. Fantasticus

Madagascar is filled with all kinds of fascinating creatures big and small, such as this satanic leaf-tailed gecko (Uroplatus phantasticus). Yes, that is its real name, and it does look a bit devilish, I must admit. However, when I first heard its full Latin name I almost keeled over in laughter. How could something be named ‚Äúsatanic‚Äù and at the same time have a Latin name that sounds like ‚Äúfantasticus‚Äù? From that point on, and forever more, this little guy will be named Mr Fantasticus to me. It sounds like a superhero name‚Ä¶.perhaps the next @marvel hero? 

Unfortunately, Mr Fantasticus is being captured (even within conservation areas) and sold to the international pet trade at alarming rates. Couple that with deforestation and loss of its natural habitat and the outlook is grim. Continued conservation is needed to protect and save Mr Fantasticus. üôè

Everywhere I look, I see people I love and admire talking about their yearly planning and sharing their processes.

I love planning. During the Phhnix days, I was a staunch defender of planning and saw first-hand how planning creates the structure to achieve any goal. It‚Äôs an infallible system.

I also find planning to be personally suffocating. I don‚Äôt know if it‚Äôs remnants of the business PTSD I have (joking, but also not), some other type of block or internal resistance, or if my intuition is telling me not to plan. Hear me out.

At the end of the day, the point of a plan is to achieve goals. A plan is a tool. Me? I‚Äôve never had an issue executing tasks or achieving goals. On the contrary, my problem in business is usually taking on too much and spending my days in overwhelm.

I‚Äôm tired of trying to do things the way that other people do them. 2024 is a year for me to get really fucking curious about my working style and test out new ways. Ways that might or might not work, but will teach me at the very least.

So I won‚Äôt be planning this year, at least not beyond the simple note listing my goals and a running to-do list. Instead, I‚Äôll be spending the majority of my working hours taking care of myself so that the work can flow like magic.

This looks like meditation, gym, beach and personal development during work time, and brief periods of intense focus to get through the actual work.

I‚Äôll be sure to let you know how it works out for me. I‚Äôm a multi-dimensional being attempting to undo every story I‚Äôve ever been told about success. If I can‚Äôt FEEL good and be in my body, then I don‚Äôt want it. No amount of success is worth my peace.

For example what we eat, what products we buy‚Ä¶if, how, when and what we drive‚Ä¶for whom we vote etc. Low hanging fruits are also to support hard working organizations like @wwfsverige , @tpw_foundation , @synchearth , @janegoodallinst , @mission_blue and @redlist_of_ecosystems to help navigating towards a resilient and healthy future for people and planet! ‚Äúconflict in congo is like a babushka (matryoshka) doll....you have conflicts sitting inside conflicts....it‚Äôs about local issues, who controls land, which chief is in power....often linked to ethnicity, because at local level ethnicity is the principle organizer of politics....at the next level, it is national power, partially due to collapse of mobutu and effects of belgian colonialism....but there it is more about using ethnicity to leverage a better position in parliament or a piece of a smuggling racket in gold....then you have the regional power politics, which mainly involves rwanda and that role really began in 1994 with the rwandan genocide....the conflict initially was not about minerals, though they became important over time to fund war efforts, esp for a country like rwanda that is small and poor....but when tantalum shot through the roof, which happened to be at a time of extreme violence, it began to shift incentives of those involved in the conflict and it was no longer about national security....around 2000 the various actors became more invested in minerals....but the war here is really about power and access to power, and that passes through local politicians. so you need to understand the politics‚Äù - jason stearns

*note: the above may serve to help understand the ‚Äúconflict in congo,‚Äù the atmosphere inside the country, and is not meant to address the past/current influence of foreign powers ‚Äúoutside‚Äù

‚ÄúThe Essence of Lightness‚Äù

A self portrait taken at midnight in Iceland last summer (the time of endless light!). üíô

So far every morning this year I‚Äôve been deep diving into my journal, writing out and contemplating what it would be like to live lighter.  To cultivate an ease and lightness in my mind, to be less busy, to be more trusting in the unknown future.  To play more, and let my inner child lead me romping through the woodlands and meadows, inspired by my imagination. 

I thought I‚Äôd share this lil blurb I brain-barfed out onto the pages this morning. ü§ì‚¨áÔ∏è

‚ÄúThis year I want to let go of pressure.  Both the pressure I put on myself, and the pressure the societal world puts on us all. 

I let go of the pressure to be perfect. The pressure to look a certain way. The pressure to post every day. I let go of the pressure I put on myself to create better and better images, videos and paintings.

This year I embrace lightness. I celebrate imperfection, because when I allow myself and my creations to be made imperfectly with my mind open, it creates space for a world of new ideas, opportunities and surprise happenings I never would have dreamed up myself in my ‚Äúperfect world‚Äù.

This year I let my true essence take the seat of my mind and being. I take time to intentionally practice dwelling in my truest state - the state of complete trust, leading to peace and joyful lightness, where I feel the most myself. 

This year I allow myself to live. Not by someone else‚Äôs standards, and not by the standards I once thought I should hold over myself. 

I live by listening. I listen intently to what brings me a sense of joy, rightness and lightness. I listen to what I can give - what I can naturally offer and help bring out in others.

I live by being kind. I live in gratitude for the freedom I‚Äôm so, so, so incredibly fortunate to have access to.

I allow this freedom to be protected, nurtured and loved, to not let this gift be taken for granted or hijacked by the endless hustling pressures of the world.

This year I embrace lightness. I put my heart first, and I let love, trust and wonder lead the way down this path of life. This one chance we have to truly live.‚Äù ü§ç

FROM MY ARCHIVE | Monhegan Island Post 05 (final):: I got my start at @natgeo in 1999 as a photo intern when I did my first story for the magazine. I was asked if I had an idea for a project and I proposed Monhegan ‚Äì a small island 10 miles off the coast of Maine. I am from New England and had lived on the Maine coast as a young adult. I had always been curious about the 2 mile long and ¬Ω mile wide island. In the summers the place overflows with tourists, but the year round population is only about 60-70. The islanders‚Äô de facto fishing territory became the Monhegan Lobster Conservation Area in 1996 with a limited season starting in October. The island‚Äôs windswept landscape, quirky community and the dramatic cliffs have inspired artists like Robert Henri, George Bellows, Rockwell Kent, Edward Hopper, Lynn Mapp Drexler and three generations of the Wyeth family to name a few. ‚Å†
‚Å†
The community took me in and sometimes chewed me up. My time and experiences there changed and shaped my life in profound and beautiful ways that continue to impact me almost 25 years later; working with photo editor Susan Welchman who took me under her wing and has been my mentor and dear friend since and within days of arriving to the island, I also met one of my best friends @tralice_pooltoyphotos ‚Å†

Again you have deliciously tender zucchini, that are also carefully hollowed out and filled with a mixture of rice, minced meat, tomatoes and spices. Unlike my last stuffed zucchini recipe, however, this one is gently simmered to perfection in a flavourful tomato sauce. 250g mince
1 cup rice, washed 
1/2 tsp baharat
1/2 tsp pepper
1/2 tbsp salt
1 tbsp tomato paste
1 med tomato, finely chopped 
1 tbsp ghee 

12 grey / Lebanese zucchini 
300g lamb loin chops or neck 
Olive oil 
1 bulb garlic
125g cherry tomatoes, halved 
1 onion, sliced into thin rings 
4 cups water or veg stock 
1 tbsp tomato paste
1 tsp sugar 
1 tsp salt 

To prepare stuffing, add all ingredients in a bowl & mix until well combined. 

In a large jug add stock or water, tomato paste, 1 tsp sugar & 1 tsp salt. Mix & set aside. 

Cut the top off the zucchini and carefully shave off the dried tips at the end without removing flesh. Hollow out the zucchini carefully removing the flesh. You want to create a cavity for stuffing without bursting or breaking zucchini.

Wash zucchini & set aside to dry.

thrilled to announce the fourth iteration of aureta x @bienendavis - to collaborate with people i love and respect has been one of life‚Äôs greatest joys - bienen davis founded in new york city in 1931, and included in the permanent collection of metropolitan museum of art, merged american design with Italian craftsmanship and soon found their bags on the sets of movies and television shows, adorning the arms of some of hollywood‚Äôs most iconic stars - fast forward 90 years to our fourth collaboration and another american treasure enters the conversation - artist @rayhowlett was the inspiration for my latest capsule collection with the brand - in the words of meredith german, creative director of BD: 

‚ÄúRay Howlett (born 1940) is an American artist primarily associated with the light and space movement. He is known as one of the pioneers of infinity light sculptures.
Howlett‚Äôs sculptures are hand ground glass geometric sculptural shapes of coated glass and electric light that create an abstract optical space larger than the piece itself, what he calls an ‚Äúoptically expanding space‚Äù. In his structural forms, illuminated graphic images appear to be floating within transparent sculptures. The internal composition and colors shift and change as the viewer moves around it using highly reflective thin-film coatings to make color shift with different angles of view. The color is dichroism.
Aureta met Ray in LA in 2018 and has been continuously inspired by his innovative body of work, becoming a leading patron of his art in hopes of maintaining his brilliant craft for generations to come.
The Ray Howlett X Aureta collaboration for Bienen Davis consists of The Kit Bracelet Bag and The R√©gine Minaudiere hand crafted in Italy and embellished with over 5,000 Swarovski crystals to reflect Ray‚Äôs incredible vision‚Äù link in bio

I could fill books on the topic of why I love living in England so much, but one of them is being able to bring in baskets of evergreens, wilted bracken, and blossoming flowers in November and February and June alike. Growing up in Norway the white winters were beautiful and definitely had its magical moments, but I love going for winter walks amongst evergreens and flowering snow drops in January while my mother tells me on the phone it‚Äôs yet another day of ice and -20 at the fjord island my parents live. I could fill baskets on end with flowering gorse, ivy, holly and bare winter branches with a few brown wilted leaves. Although flowers are beautiful, give me a branch with or without green leaves any day. So our little cottage, my garden studio and car are always filled with evidence of my never ending love for nature, bringing the outside in. It simply brings joy, the everyday kind, that cost nothing, but truly makes all the difference. Which brings me back to yesterday‚Äôs launch of my new ongoing stillife series, of wilted leaves and twisted twigs, a homage to the muted tones of the wilted botanical world of the English countryside. #myenglishcountryside

And then there is this woman, my mother. Today is Mother‚Äôs Day in Norway, a date I only remember because my sister reminds me, but I somehow always remember the date for it here in England. But no matter the date, this woman needs to be celebrated. She‚Äôs simply my heart, my beating heart, and hearing her say it will all be well, is all the assurance I need to keep going when times are hard. She so incredibly warm you simply cannot sit next to her without feeling uplifted. Her wisdom has carried me through everything life has to offer, and now to see my daughter lean on her for comfort, for love, for consistency in friendship, and for stability, when her young life is facing more challenges her age should need to carry on her shoulders, is so beautiful to watch. My mother brings joy and laughter that is infectious, and she has this beautiful way of laughing at herself which brightens any room she enters. I know I‚Äôm lucky, but I also know it‚Äôs hard work, because every time I tell her about people who comment on how lucky I am to have her, she smiles and simply tells me it‚Äôs a choice she makes every morning when she gets up, to be the best she can be, and it‚Äôs work, it‚Äôs a consistent choice. I try to mirror her ability to love during hardship and to never give up. And when I fall asleep at night next to my wonderful little girl, I count myself lucky to have them both in my life, and do my best in becoming for my daughter, what my mother is to me, a rock of love to lean on and to unwaveringly be encouraged to reach any goal and dream I may have. In this week‚Äôs newsletter I wrote about portraiture with direct light, and used a series shot with my mother as an example. You can read it via a link in my profile to ‚ÄúThe Photography Workshop‚Äù newsletter. All previous newsletters are archived there, and you can access them all should you miss it on the day they are sent out. I hope you‚Äôll enjoy it! Happy Norwegian Mother‚Äôs Day to all of you. xx

Simplicity, slowing down and creating intimate moments at home. Looking back it‚Äôs the quieter days that hold the most special memories with my family vs the big parties or grand trips. 

Many of us have our days filled with appointments, time to get from here to there, pick up this and that‚Ä¶ we end up yearning for those slower moments but then are also programmed to think and feel it‚Äôs ‚Äúboring‚Äù if we‚Äôre not constantly on the move. ü§î 

Why not make those times at home beautiful? Turn ordinary moments into extraordinary‚Ä¶just by switching our mind set‚Ä¶just by looking a little deeper and enjoying the beauty in the simplicity. 

I remember one summer as a kid, the AC went out for a good portion of the season. It was hot and humid (back east where I grew up.) My mom hung pretty sheets in the hallway to direct the airflow of the portable fan we had plugged in. My sisters and I gathered around with snacks and movies. I still remember the shadows dancing in our room, as we lowered the curtains to keep the heat from the sun out a bit. It felt magical and special, even though yes, we were hot‚Ä¶but we weren‚Äôt  focused on that at the time‚Ä¶

It‚Äôs easy to romanticize everyday moments if we let ourselves see things that way‚Ä¶.a little more childlike, find some beauty and magic in it all‚Ä¶

El Camino Real de Baja California runs from Tijuana to Loreto, Mexico. Many are familiar with El Camino Real of Alta California (modern-day California), which is lined with bells and passes through cities like Los Angeles and San Francisco. The old road in Baja has been forgotten, even though it played a massive role in the development of the whole region. The roads were originally trails made by the indigenous communities of the region, whose people were killed, died from diseases and were used as slave labor to build the road by the Spanish.
 
 
-Felipe Villa Poblano, who has lived next to the Mission Santa Gertrudis for 26 years, has a small store and looks after the mission. Mission Santa Gertrudis was established in 1751 by the Jesuits to convert Cochim√≠ Indians.

- Mother Mary stands in a side room of the Mission San Ignacio, which was founded in 1728 by the Jesuits.

Slowing down has been essential in my wellness journey. As we embrace these last few moments of winter, let‚Äôs try to soak it all in, not count down the days till spring time. I used to be angry at myself for wanting to slow down. I used to struggle with the change in seasons, but I‚Äôve recently embraced how healing seasonality could be if we embrace it. The Earth, the animals, and plants are resting in winter, we should be too. We are more in sync with the Earth than we think. 

Moving slowly, embracing the season, and allowing ourselves to rest. Why is this something we so often fight when it‚Äôs what our bodies need the most? 
.
The sun is shining today, but we had a series of rainy days here in Tucson recently and the cloudy, cozy days gave me the nudge I needed to rest and recharge. After chatting with a few of you, it seems I‚Äôm not alone in needing to make that *conscious decision* to slow down. 
.
It‚Äôs been a while since I got personal on the blog, but if you‚Äôre interested in a bit of reflection, how I stopped attacking my nervous system, and embraced this slow season of life, head to the link in my bio. üß°

2023 is gone, just a number! It‚Äôs been a year filled with travels in Pakistan, Uzbekistan, Spain, Azerbaijan, Canada, Tajikistan, India etc‚Ä¶
It was interesting to meander through life between being a photographer, a farmer and be present for the family.
I thought of god a bit, all triggered by a story on Zoroastrianism for National Geographic magazine (coming up). How and why do we often inherit the feeling of being watched by God, god like a massive cctv system‚Ä¶ religion the opium of the people?
Probably god is busy with a lot more than watching you‚Ä¶ Is your god a vengeful one or a god that you will live with and whose law you must respect, like gravity? Lots of fun questions with no real need for answers..

Here is a serene scene, mixing all religious influences (at least to my eye!), in a place that has seen Animism, Buddhism, Zoroastrianism and more recently Islam (ismaili faith). It‚Äôs in an ‚Äúostone‚Äù, a shrine in Tajikistan‚Äôs Wakhan corridor, adorned with ibex and Marco Polo horns - and a triangle of stones for the ‚Äúshirogh‚Äù (the candle of cotton dipped in oil), lit for special occasion (for Jumarat, Eid or for Didor, the birthday of the Aga Khan etc). Azom Khon, the caretaker, is praying for me before I leave. It was beautiful so I pulled back and took a picture.

I will be sharing pictures here from my recent travels until I leave for SE Asia on February 20th.
Love and light for 2024.

Spinach and ricotta shells üòã

This recipe is one of my favourite pasta dishes, so easy to make and a great one for entertaining too ü§åüèº

Ingredients:‚Ä®- 250g ricotta‚Ä®- 3 tbsp lemon juice‚Ä®- 100g chopped spinach‚Ä®- 1 tbsp minced garlic‚Ä®- 1 tsp salt‚Ä®- cracked pepper, to taste‚Ä®- 700g passata‚Ä®- handful of fresh basil leaves‚Ä®- 12 pasta shells‚Ä®- sprinkle of parmesan‚Ä®- 1 tbsp pine nuts

Method:
1. Preheat the oven to 180¬∞C fan-forced and place a large pot of water to boil over the stove, on high heat.
2. Once water is boiled, add the pasta shells to the pot. Cook as per packet instructions, ensuring not to overcook. Then, drain and rinse with cold water.
3. Add passata, fresh basil leaves, 1/2 tsp salt and pepper to a 30cm x 20cm baking dish and mix, spreading evenly.
4. Add ricotta, lemon, spinach, garlic, 1/2 tsp salt and pepper to a bowl and mix well to combine.
5. One-by-one, spoon approx 2 tbsp of the ricotta mixture into each shell and place into the baking dish. Repeat until shells and ricotta mixture are all used up.
6. Sprinkle with parmesan and pine nuts, and place into the oven to bake for 15-20 minutes, or until pine nuts and pasta shells begin to brown.
7. Serve hot & enjoy!

The sun peeked through every now and then this morning, and it felt like a warm hug. It was needed, it‚Äôs been raining for what feels like weeks on end, and although I don‚Äôt mind a drizzle or soaking, I turned my face towards the sun like moth to the flame. It‚Äôs the first day of the week, and although my birthday isn‚Äôt until Wednesday, I‚Äôm calling it my birthday week, and will unashamedly celebrate with little sprinkles of happiness every day of this week. Between a mug of tea at my daughter‚Äôs morning school assembly, and a well brewed coffee from the brilliant @bean_shot_coffee in town I stood on a street corner, when someone shook their head, and stopped themselves from saying what was on their mind and said: ‚ÄúIt doesn‚Äôt matter‚Äù‚Ä¶and walked away. And I thought to myself, everything matters! Every moment of every day matters, everything we have in our hearts that we want to say, matters, the time we spend with someone else matters, we all matter, and life is way too short and way too long to not do, say or be, what we know in our hearts matter to us. I stood there in a small patch of sunlight, re-listening to those very words in my head. It‚Äôs the words of giving up on what matters, and it reminded me to always lean in, showing up, and daring to say what matters to me. It reminded me of being brave and standing tall amidst hardship, and about never losing sight of what‚Äôs important in life. I walked away with a reminder to live more, which brings me back to birthdays, a day I rarely if ever celebrate, feeling a bit silly about it all, and that it didn‚Äôt matter. Rinpung Monastery, Paro, Bhutan. A ‚Äúdzong‚Äù is the word they use  in Bhutan for a fortress/monastery. These beautiful structures with giant walls reveal a lot about Bhutan‚Äôs unique culture. First, it is a defensible fortress--a holdover from days when wars were still happening. You can‚Äôt see from the picture I took here, but the walls descend further, so there‚Äôs no way for attackers to climb up or get inside. There‚Äôs tiny slits  around the Dzong where people inside can shoot arrows at attackers on the outside! üèπI‚Äôve seen 10 fortresses like this in throughout Bhutan, and they‚Äôre usually built on a hillside with a strategic view of the valley, and, if the view isn‚Äôt so great, there‚Äôs a secondary watchtower in a better position. But what are they defending? I am just learning, but there‚Äôs a unique confluence of activity inside each Dzong: besides a military fortress, today, Dzong‚Äôs are homes for monks, and a spiritual center, but they also house all kinds of offices‚Äîthink of it like the combination church, DMV, a civil court, an architecture planning office, and anything else related to the city‚Äôs administration. It shows how there is a lack of separation between ‚Äúchurch and state‚Äù‚Ä¶ In Bhutan, their philosophical and ‚Äúreligious‚Äù beliefs (some say Buddhism is not a religion, but a philosophical perspective), are integrated with the government, not separated. üéäMore Bhutanese are beginning to dress like Westerners, but when you visit the Dzong, you are required to where the traditional dress of the Bhutanese people. To foreign eyes, it makes for a colorful and exciting experience‚Äîyou feel like you‚Äôre in the 16th century watching the activity inside, even though people might be there to get architectural plans approved, or to get a divorce, or something else that seems very ‚Äúmodern‚Äù to us. Ah yes, and the chilis‚Ä¶ I had to include the chilis drying in the sun. Bhutanese add chilis to almost every dish (even in their rice); certainly there will be chilis in every meal! The chilis are dried outside, typically on the roof of homes. üè† Drying can take a month! ‚òÄÔ∏èI think I‚Äôll be adding chilis to dishes when i get back home! üòÄ

Wyoming has quickly become one of my favorite backpacking destinations. Two years ago I spent a week in the Wind River Range, then last summer I joined @elisabethontheroad as she documented our climb up Cloud Peak in the Bighorn Mountains for @visitwyoming

I‚Äôve followed the work of plein air painters from this state before I ever picked up a camera. It‚Äôs been fun growing familiar with the language of the landscape first hand, to see the peaks and valleys that translated to such inspiration. 

Finding beauty can be straightforward, it shines unabashed, but exploring what you have to say about a place takes time. It may even be through the creative process itself that you discover it. I often learn as much during a week on the computer with a digital paintbrush, as a week on the trail. Wouldn‚Äôt trade the epiphanies provided by either.

If your curious about the specifics of our climb, you can find Elisabeth‚Äôs article at TravelWyoming.com. #ThatsWY #WYresponsibly

‚Äúconflict in congo is like a babushka (matryoshka) doll....you have conflicts sitting inside conflicts....it‚Äôs about local issues, who controls land, which chief is in power....often linked to ethnicity, because at local level ethnicity is the principle organizer of politics....at the next level, it is national power, partially due to collapse of mobutu and effects of belgian colonialism....but there it is more about using ethnicity to leverage a better position in parliament or a piece of a smuggling racket in gold....then you have the regional power politics, which mainly involves rwanda and that role really began in 1994 with the rwandan genocide....the conflict initially was not about minerals, though they became important over time to fund war efforts, esp for a country like rwanda that is small and poor....but when tantalum shot through the roof, which happened to be at a time of extreme violence, it began to shift incentives of those involved in the conflict and it was no longer about national security....around 2000 the various actors became more invested in minerals....but the war here is really about power and access to power, and that passes through local politicians. so you need to understand the politics‚Äù - jason stearns

*note: the above may serve to help understand the ‚Äúconflict in congo,‚Äù the atmosphere inside the country, and is not meant to address the past/current influence of foreign powers ‚Äúoutside‚Äù

üòû This is difficult for me to write. Last week I stepped outside my comfort zone and shared a very personal goal of mine to have my book make the New York Times Best Seller list. üò± The list isn‚Äôt released until this Sunday but my editor at NatGeo said publishers find out a few days early and she would call me right away. I got the call. She shared the sad news that I didn‚Äôt make the list. üòî I kept it together on the call..but the tears came hard as soon as we said bye. I‚Äôm surprised I care so much about this. I cried for about 5 minutes and after a great pep talk from a supportive husband was able to pick myself up. ü•π

üíõ I want to make it clear that above all, I‚Äôm extremely proud of my book and don‚Äôt want this to cast any sort of shadow over the past 4 years that were nothing but a positive experience of writing and creating this treasure for families all around the world. üåé The quality of my hard work is definitely more important than the accolade of New York Times Best Seller. But I think, if I were to try my best to explain why I‚Äôm feeling so sad and even slightly embarrassed it‚Äôs because 2 things: I‚Äôve never wanted anything like this for myself. I‚Äôm sure so many other mothers out there can relate. I endlessly cheer and support my family, but rarely do I want something so purely for myself. This was that for me. ‚ù§Ô∏è

Secondly, the Bucket List community has rallied so hard behind me. I have have felt it every day of this journey. I was excited to celebrate this achievement all of us together. ‚ù§Ô∏èüíôüíö You‚Äôve done so much for me. Thx to you, we‚Äôve surpassed NatGeo‚Äôs presale records. I‚Äôm going to keep my head up and focus on the positive. There‚Äôs still chance I may make the list in future weeks so I‚Äôll keep trying my best. Positive reviews of my book on Amazon and Goodreads help so much. ‚≠êÔ∏è I want you to know that I screenshot your thoughtful reviews and every time you share my book on Instagram in such cute creative ways and add it to a journal I‚Äôve been keeping of this book publishing journey. Thank you for being a part of my story and all the ups and downs. This day is a down for me. But I know I can get back up..‚ù§Ô∏è Jess

This 8-ingredient baked feta recipe is simple, delicious & oh so cozy. Serve it as a main course or an appetizer, along with warm bread for scooping up the crumbly feta cheese and rich tomato sauce ü§§

Ingredients
* 2 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil, more for drizzling
* 1 teaspoon cumin seeds
* 1 bunch lacinato kale, stems removed and torn into bite sized pieces
* 2 cups tomato sauce, or Marinara Sauce
* 1 1/2 cups cooked chickpeas, drained and rinsed
* 1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice, plus wedges for serving
* 1 12-ounce block of feta, cut into 1/2-inch planks
* freshly ground black pepper
* pinch of red pepper flakes
* warm pita or baguette, for serving

Instructions
* Preheat the oven to 350¬∞F.
* Heat a 10 or 12-inch oven-safe skillet over medium heat and add the oil. Add the cumin seeds and let them sizzle gently for a minute or two. Add the kale in batches, letting each handful shrink and wilt before adding the next.
* When the last of the kale has wilted, add the tomato sauce, chickpeas, lemon juice, and 1/2 cup water. Stir and let it come to a simmer.
* Nestle the feta slices into the sauce and sprinkle with freshly ground black pepper. Slide the skillet into the oven and bake until the feta has softened, about 15 minutes. Drizzle with olive oil and a pinch of red pepper flakes and serve with warm pita and lemon wedges.

news flash: last week, just north of cabo near our hotel in baja, a mama sea turtle came ashore to lay a clutch of eggs. she made three nests, spending ~20 minutes in each (the first and last nest are visible in the second video) and used her fins to push sand and bury herself deeper into the sand before laying the eggs, before making her way back to the ocean and vanishing into a wave. according to the man in this video, the eggs should hatch in 1-2 months and the turtles (loggerheads) lay several nests in order to maximize reproductive output + help protect the eggs from predators üê¢

‚ÄúYou‚Äôre meant to be a fitness professional, but you‚Äôre weak, unfit & pathetic!‚Äú - these are not words from other people, they‚Äôre words from my own head! üò´ Yep, I can be my own worst enemy! üòî Words have great power & we need to be careful what we tell ourselves. 
I‚Äôm actively working on reprogramming the way I talk to myself to be more positive, kinder & more encouraging. I need to believe in myself as I believe it‚Äôs the first & most important step towards achieving success!
This workout absolutely destroyed me. ü•µ But I did it & I‚Äôm proud of myself! üëèüèº
Getting back into my training has been a struggle. I‚Äôm lacking motivation & consistency feels like a distant dream. I‚Äôve been beating myself up over the strength & fitness I‚Äôve lost. Rehabbing injuries for several months has left me feeling discouraged, & it‚Äôs hard not to compare myself to who I used to be.

Fitness professionals like me are not immune to struggles. We may know WHAT to do, but we still have to put in the work for results. The mental game is the toughest part, especially when starting over feels like a never-ending cycle. Life throws curveballs that make it hard to stick with something long-term. But I‚Äôm determined to reclaim my fitness, strength, & get back to feeling incredible again.

Negative self-talk doesn‚Äôt do us any good. Deep down, we know this, but we need reminders. We have to consciously choose to focus on the positive, even when it feels like an uphill battle. It‚Äôs not easy, but it‚Äôs necessary.

Remember; If it were easy, everyone would be doing it. The path to fitness is tough, but it‚Äôs worth every bit of effort. So I‚Äôm taking charge, setting realistic goals, & celebrating every small victory along the way. Consistency is my anchor, & I‚Äôm committed to showing up for myself every single day.

It does get easier, I know this because I‚Äôve done it many times before. Each day I put in the effort, I know I‚Äôll get stronger & fitter. Progress may be slow, but it‚Äôs progress nonetheless. 
Let‚Äôs embrace the struggle, be proud of our efforts, & keep pushing forward. We have the power to transform our lives, & it‚Äôs time to unleash that power. üëäüèº

Like over 200,000 people in the Portland area these past days, my dad‚Äôs house lost power and being over 70 and not very mobile,  with temps in the teens, he wanted us to come get him. Unfortunately all the roads to his house were closed and he was going to have to stay home for the night.
I awoke in the multiple times filled with worry for him, and for all the people without power or shelter. A fear gripping my heart for him and them. 

His phone has little power left and no way to charge it.

The next day, a generous neighbor was able to pick him up and deliver him to our heat cranked home. And I‚Äôm just so filled with gratitude for what we have. The joy of watching my dad laughing hysterically from the pleasure of getting stoned and eating his first @sarahminnick_ üçï, salad, and ice cream.
The joy of bundling up the child and playing till her lips were blue but knowing we had somewhere warm to rest.

I‚Äôm grateful for our friend Larry for helping my dad get to us.
For family of blood and chosen.

Climbing brings us together.  Once you challenge yourself with gravity and share this experience with your friends something changes. It's the international language of belaying and spotting. It's the same everywhere. You have to trust someone to achieve your goals. 

@memphisroxclimbing has been a flywheel for the good that climbing brings. Built in the shell of a supermarket with a state of the facility, Rox is bringing gym climbing and outdoor experiences to South Memphis.

With a pay as one can model, the gym is open to everyone. Climbing as I was introduced to it was free. The cliffs were at  end of the road and my dad and his buddies had the gear and knowledge. I still recall the moment when climbing and being outdoors latched on. It's that same emotion that we see with the people we welcome to the crag, mountain and gym. Let's keep that going! 

The freedom that climbing brings comes at a cost. The facility and staff are monthly obligations. In business, as in climbing, the unexpected happens. In this case a burst water pipe needs immediate attention. To keep Rox a safe place (it's a polling station, health care facility and restaurant) the security team needs immediate funding. Going without costs the program more. 

Rox has been a part of my life for the past six years. I've made new friends, shared backcountry experience & knowledge while climbing outdoors and learned from each other on how to address the challenges of race in the United States. 

If you believe in the mission of @memphisroxclimbing please consider a donation. It will be put to good use. If you have the chance to visit Memphis, stop by the gym. You'll find family by the time you have warmed up.

Today we decided to check out a park in Saigon. Creating a little reference point gives us a little mission to embark on and get our steps in üòä This is  always a nice way to discover small gems or see places you would not be able to read or watch about. On our walkie walk, we were able to see the contrast in the city. One of my pics shows the old way of living off a stream (how my parents described their life growing up), and behind it are the new skyscrapers. 

As we walked, we discovered more street foods, mini restaurants, and cafes. I got some sugarcane juice off an auntie from a side stall and then stumbled into a little oasis off a super busy bustling road. It was a little coffee stale with lots of unique and local plants surrounding it. Great place for coffee and plant enthusiasts ü™¥ There were little tables and seats hidden around an array of hanging plants. Later I found out it was a plant shop too! This was a nice little break stop for another refresher. Troy got his iced coffee and so we got to sit amongst all these pretty greenery. Everything is such a contrast in Saigon. You see old vs new everywhere, the crazy busy hustle of traffic, and Vietnamese taking their naps in the mist of all the chaos in the streets. I really enjoy observing üëÄ and wondering how people adapt to the places they live in.

This literally saved my life (and grades) in uni!! ‚¨áÔ∏è‚úÖüíØüë©üèº‚Äçüéì
-
The Issue üò≠: 
There‚Äôs SO MUCH more content to learn in uni than compared to high-school üìö
Furthermore, lecturers are often experts in their field, with years and years of experience, and when they get excited about what they‚Äôre teaching, they may go way way overboard, and share more than you need to know for your exams.

The Solution ‚ú®: 
Focus on high-yield content. This is the content that will get you the most marks on your exam & assignments, and thus is the best use of your time.

You can find this through the learning objectives (usually at the start of each lecture or in your study guide) or by doing practice exams (as often the same questions/topics are repeated). üìù

An effective method I used was to turn each dot-point in the learning objectives into a question, then look through the lecture slides and other materials to answer the question, rather than reading every single page in the textbook or slides. ‚úÖ‚úÖ

There‚Äôs a balance between surface and substance, the aesthetics of an image and its meaning. I tend to think craft is important, but offers diminishing returns. In contrast, the possibilities for conceptual exploration are endless. It‚Äôs the difference between learning a language and finding what you have to say with it.

My favorite time in art history was between the late 1800‚Äôs and the early 1900‚Äôs, when the method used to create something started gaining awareness of its contribution to content. An interest in the mechanics of light and sight created the dappled visual color mixing of the impressionists. An interest in the mechanics of time and space gave birth to the multiple overlaid perspectives of cubism. I keep thinking about this as I flew about the mountains, collecting images from multiple moments and perspective.

Does any of this matter to the viewer and the final? Maybe. There are plenty of images I‚Äôve enjoyed for their ideas, and plenty for aesthetics alone. But on this side of the image, the one of discovery and creation, building something with a conceptual foundation makes all the difference between a meaningful process and a simply stylish one. It‚Äôs powerfully good to stay in touch with that little kid inside, who endlessly asks ‚Äúwhy?!‚Äù

If you‚Äôre looking for a new healthy breakfast or snack to add to your rotation, try this green smoothie! It‚Äôs thick and frosty, lightly sweet, and brimming with fresh produce like citrus, spinach, and banana üíö

Ingredients
* 1 cup frozen spinach or kale
* ¬Ω frozen banana
* ¬Ω tablespoon almond butter
* 1 to 2 cups peeled and frozen orange segments, or frozen pineapple or mango chunks
* ¬Ω teaspoon chia seeds, optional
* 1 cup almond milk, plus more as needed to blend
* Handful of ice

Instructions
* In a blender, place the spinach, banana, almond butter, 1 cup frozen fruit, and chia seeds, if using. Add the almond milk and blend until smooth, adding more almond milk as needed to blend. Add the ice and blend again. ‚Ä®
* Taste and add more frozen fruit if you‚Äôd like your smoothie to be sweeter. Blend until smooth, adding more almond milk as needed.

We bear the fruits of every action we take. Karma is a universal law of action. Both the intended and unintended consequences of our actions rest on our shoulders. I don‚Äôt see this a zero sum game of winners and losers or some harsh deity that issues judgement. Instead, every experience is all about learning, growing and evolving. 

An action we take with the best intentions reverberates for lifetimes with both positive and negative impact on our lives and the lives of those around us. We can be working through the residual impact for as long as need in order to integrate the spiritual lesson. Repetition isn‚Äôt always due to failure. Sometimes it‚Äôs about seeing another person or reaching a deeper layer. 

Once we are strong enough to see ourselves clearly, we are ready to really go through the process of spiritual awakening. Everything we do in three practice prepares us for increasingly deeper levels of self-realization. We can‚Äôt rush. We can only go at our own pace and trust that what is meant to happen will happen when it‚Äôs meant to happen.

A little monday morning motivation. I loved this sound clip when I heard it. We can apply it to so many things‚Ä¶asking for help as a parent, going after what you want in your career or diving deeper in your relationship. Taking that step to move forward and get out of a rut‚Ä¶ the list can go and on. I think we‚Äôve all have had trouble with doing one or all of these things at some point in our lives.
‚ú®
With each step forward or heck, within any moment of self doubt, I find myself reflecting on the last year, or five years or ten years and realizing how much growth I‚Äôve experienced as an individual. It can be hard for many of us to see it at times, but if we look, it‚Äôs there. 

Rob and I were just talking about this the other night after we put our 3 year old to bed. 3 year old?! Wait‚Ä¶almost 4 year old‚Ä¶what?!? We‚Äôre coming up on 10 years of marriage and never did we think we‚Äôd be in Arizona with a toddler, build a house or have traveled to all the places we have. None of this was the plan ten years ago sitting on a beach during our honeymoon. There never really was a plan, but every step we took, it felt like a step towards a more authentic self. A step towards a happier, more flexible life, creating space to explore and love and learn and stumble unapologetically. We created that space for ourselves together as a couple and still continue to grow and learn. Now we get to create that as parents together for a special little human who makes us feel more than we ever thought we could. 
üß°
This is turning into a novel and I‚Äôm writing this out at night (to post in the morning) which is probably why i feel all the feels‚Ä¶but all this to say, I love these words and I think it‚Äôs the encouragement we need to remind ourselves and our loved ones to go after what we want ‚Ä¶create the type of life that brings our souls that much closer to feeling full. üôå

MORE GLUTES IN YOUR DEADLIFT üçë OR MORE HAMSTRINGS üçñ Here‚Äôs how you get your aim right‚Ä¶

GLUTE FOCUSED DEADLIFT üçë
This requires more STRETCH of the glute muscle to occur because more stretch = increased tension = more activation & work required to contract the muscles again. And more work = MORE GROWTH!
üëâüèº so what do you need to do? 
Increase the amount of knee bend and lower the hips more. This creates a deeper fold at the hips (and also less tension in the hamstring) increasing the recruitment of the glutes üëåüèº

HAMSTRING FOCUSED DEADLIFT üçñ
The same principle applies. You need to create more stretch & length in the hamstrings compared to the glutes.
üëâüèº so what do you need to do?
Less bend in the knees (bust still a slight bend üòâ) and keep the hips higher as you lower the bar.

I don‚Äôt always know how to write a humanist caption for what I report on. I was down on the border in #eaglepass TX covering hopeful and desperate migrants crossing the Rio Grande. Most were coming from Venezuela. Many had been on the road for over a year. The infant had been born while on the road. The definition of a stateless refugee. 
And the last leg of their desperate trip was a raging river, and a shore filled with concertina razor wire and armed National Guard. 
The US border patrol would cut the wire that the National Guard put up to let people in. Children and women first, then men. 

My dad came through Ellis Island as a child, and never had to face what these people have.

This is one of the most unique looking frogs you can find in Costa Rica, known as the Coronated Tree Frog. It's name comes from the fact that at certain angles, it looks as if it is wearing a crown. They can be found in the mountains around the area known as Sarapique, just north of San Jose. It is one of many different species of frogs and snakes that we look for during my Costa Rica wildlife workshops I run each January.

It's the slow life for me now.

Just a few years ago, I traveled from country to country, experiencing something new every week, every day, every minute. I was filled with impressions and experiences, which I cherish deeply and will keep remembering them forever. But I came to realize that the true essence of travel isn't just about the landscapes or the sights.

It's about connections. The kind that grows stronger the longer you stay, becoming a part of communities. Of families.

Mongolia taught me this valuable lesson, and there's no looking back.

I could fill books on the topic of why I love living in England so much, but one of them is being able to bring in baskets of evergreens, wilted bracken, and blossoming flowers in November and February and June alike. Growing up in Norway the white winters were beautiful and definitely had its magical moments, but I love going for winter walks amongst evergreens and flowering snow drops in January while my mother tells me on the phone it‚Äôs yet another day of ice and -20 at the fjord island my parents live. I could fill baskets on end with flowering gorse, ivy, holly and bare winter branches with a few brown wilted leaves. Although flowers are beautiful, give me a branch with or without green leaves any day. So our little cottage, my garden studio and car are always filled with evidence of my never ending love for nature, bringing the outside in. It simply brings joy, the everyday kind, that cost nothing, but truly makes all the difference. Which brings me back to yesterday‚Äôs launch of my new ongoing stillife series, of wilted leaves and twisted twigs, a homage to the muted tones of the wilted botanical world of the English countryside. #myenglishcountryside

I am humbled to share another remarkable conservation story from Kenya: the resurgence of eastern black rhinos from the brink of extinction. In a pivotal moment, Kenya is reclaiming its role as a haven for these creatures, establishing a vital breeding population at @Loisaba_Conservancy in Laikipia, Kenya, where they have been absent for the past half-century mainly due to poaching and long ago,  trophy hunting. This first image shows the moment a rhino was resuscitated after it stopped breathing and quickly released. The arduous tasks of tracking, darting, and relocating 21 of these critically endangered giants, each weighing over a ton, posed formidable challenges, yet the teams from @kenyawildlifeservice executed the operation with unparalleled expertise and dedication. Their efforts offer a glimmer of hope for the future of these magnificent creatures. The final image shows the skull of the last rhino poached in the 1970s resting beneath a celestial canopy, symbolizing this hopeful shift as Kenya now stands  as a nation that is expanding habitat and bolstering rhino populations. With approximately 80% of the world's remaining eastern black rhinos under its protection, Kenya is safeguarding endangered populations for future generations. 

I want to sincerely thank all the partners and encourage you to follow @nature_africa @nature_org @loisaba_conservancy  @kenyawildlifeservice  @olpejeta @sandiegozoo @spaceforgiants  @elewanacollection @lewaconservancy 

Photos by @amivitale

Flew to the land down under few days ago and I finally got to see Canberra. I must say this beautiful city is more quiet and laidback as compared to the vibrant and busy Sydney.

With many things in mind, visiting the National Gallery of Australia is on the top our list. Inside it we saw a lot of amazing masterpieces, but what struck me the most is James Turrell's 'Within without' Skyspace, a viewing chamber (or a "stupa") highlighted by turquoise water that surrounds it. This work shows the way we percieve the sky depending on the time of the day. They say it is at its most dramatic and complex form during dawn and dusk, marking the transition between day and night. Truly a remarkable work of art where nature, art, and architecture meet!

Excited to share more snaps and stories from the many things we saw and learned about this city. Big thanks to my travel partner @bigskynationph for keeping us connected everywhere we go with their travel wi-fi!

Shot with @sonyphinc #Alpha7III, 16-35mm f/4.

The sun peeked through every now and then this morning, and it felt like a warm hug. It was needed, it‚Äôs been raining for what feels like weeks on end, and although I don‚Äôt mind a drizzle or soaking, I turned my face towards the sun like moth to the flame. It‚Äôs the first day of the week, and although my birthday isn‚Äôt until Wednesday, I‚Äôm calling it my birthday week, and will unashamedly celebrate with little sprinkles of happiness every day of this week. Between a mug of tea at my daughter‚Äôs morning school assembly, and a well brewed coffee from the brilliant @bean_shot_coffee in town I stood on a street corner, when someone shook their head, and stopped themselves from saying what was on their mind and said: ‚ÄúIt doesn‚Äôt matter‚Äù‚Ä¶and walked away. And I thought to myself, everything matters! Every moment of every day matters, everything we have in our hearts that we want to say, matters, the time we spend with someone else matters, we all matter, and life is way too short and way too long to not do, say or be, what we know in our hearts matter to us. I stood there in a small patch of sunlight, re-listening to those very words in my head. It‚Äôs the words of giving up on what matters, and it reminded me to always lean in, showing up, and daring to say what matters to me. It reminded me of being brave and standing tall amidst hardship, and about never losing sight of what‚Äôs important in life. I walked away with a reminder to live more, which brings me back to birthdays, a day I rarely if ever celebrate, feeling a bit silly about it all, and that it didn‚Äôt matter. Well, this is a new year, and if there ever was a time for change, it is now. So, a birthday week it is, with daily sprinkles of joy to celebrate another year around the sun, and that at the end of the day it can only rain for so long, before the sun finally comes out again;)

Una relaci√≥n de pareja no es lo que la mayor√≠a piensa que es. No se despierta uno cada ma√±ana para hacer el desayuno y comer juntos. No son abrazos eternos en la cama y palabras dulces hasta que los dos se duerman. No es una casa limpia llena de risas y amor todos los d√≠as. No es perfecci√≥n.

Pero en esas amargas experiencias se encuentran los m√°s bellos regalos. Una relaci√≥n de pareja es tener en tu vida a alguien que se preocupa por ti a pesar de qu√© y qui√©n eres, a pesar de tus errores e imperfecciones.
Es alguien que ayuda en este duro trabajo de la vida. Es colaboraci√≥n mutua, hacerse la cena entre los dos y sentarse juntos, a una hora tard√≠a, porque los dos tuvieron un d√≠a loco. Es tener una crisis emocional y que tu pareja se acueste contigo y te sostenga, y te diga que todo va a estar bien. Y t√∫ le creas.

PILATES FOR RUNNERS üëü If you‚Äôre a runner, sprinter, or even walker, you should be doing this!

Building strength in the glutes, stability in the hips & maintaining active feet is so important for efficient & injury free leg driven km‚Äôs (or miles!) üèÉüèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüí®

I‚Äôve sped these videos up a little bit so remember to do each exercise slowly and with purpose!

TRY BEFORE RUNNING:
1-3 rounds depending how much time you have (the more often you do these, the better results you will get üí™üèº)

‚ñ™Ô∏è1. CLAM SEQUENCE
x10 each side

- do all 3 exercises in a row, making sure you don‚Äôt collapse in the bottom ribcage between each exercise.
- keep the hips still (like there are in concrete) 

üí•WORKS: Glute med & min - important for good lower body gait & hip stability

‚ñ™Ô∏è 2. SL TUCK CIRCLES
x10 each side

- keep belly button pulled in as you hold hips high & aim to keep hips still.

üí•WORKS: Glute max, med & min / hip flexors / abs - helps build hip stability during leg movement

‚ñ™Ô∏è3. SL EXTENDED RDL
x10 each side

- standing leg always has a slight bend
- fold at the hips & keep spine long (sit into standing leg a bit deeper)

üí•WORKS: Glute max, med & min, quads, hip flexor - improves balance, hip stability & foot strength

‚ñ™Ô∏è4. HIP HIKES
x10 each side

- move slowly & through full range on every rep (full up - full down)

üí•WORKS: Glute med & min / obliques - improves hip stability & lower body gait

‚ñ™Ô∏è5. FOOT SEQUENCE
x10 each side

Heel-Toe
- as you lean back pick up all 10 toes. Spread them as wide as you can as you roll foot forward then rise to toes.

Outdide-Inside
- slight bend in the knees & aim to find edges of your feet while spreading toes.

üí•WORKS: Calves / Smaller foot muscles - important for good foot biomechanics and strength (our feet become weak as we are constantly in shoes!)

Let me know if you‚Äôre a runner and what you think of these exercises! ‚ò∫Ô∏è #runningexercises #pilatesforrunners #runningrehab

Scotland Fix of the Day: Seaside villages in Scotland have always beckoned to me, evoking romantic ideals of another life, another way of living. Actual life has a way of being more complicated, of course, but exploring these communities (in all their variety) speaks to an inner longing that I tugs at me. 
 
1. Pennan sit snug along the base of the cliff on the Moray Firth, perhaps one of the most iconic of seaside villages.
2. Port Ellen on Islay is another of those planned communities that stretch along the shore with colorful boats pulled up onto the grass.
3. Craighouse on Jura can‚Äôt be very big because the whole island is only 200 people, but it offers quiet views of the bay from the bench by the war memorial.
4. Stromness in Orkney sidles along the bay, originally laid out when when sea captains bound for Canada and the Antarctic built their houses with a dock out back. 
5. St. Andrews Cathedral offers spectacular views down on the ruins and the graveyard from atop St. Rule‚Äôs Tower, views that stretch off to the famous strand. 
6. Pierowall on Westray, circles the bay, a North Sea village dating back through history like a chronicle of archeological ages, at least as far back as the Neolithic. 
7. Elgol on the Isle of Skye probably has more boats than houses. There is a school and a pier with views out to Rum in the distance, and stunning rock formations washed endlessly by the sea. 

I‚Äôm still exploring seaside villages. Which ones do you recommend? I‚Äôll add them to my list. Thanks.

Since the 1990s, The Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has experienced a decades-long war that has roots in a struggle for power. Please DONATE to CKI: ‚Å†
Congo Kids Initiative (CKI) is specifically for children who have lost their parents and communities to the conflict. St. Kizito is a facility located in the town of Bunia at the site of some of the most extreme violence. They work with local partners that determine targets of how these children can be provided with the most loving, sustainable, and nurturing environment. I saw @karlieplace post a bit of this editing style on a reel yesterday and I just thought it was amazing. Shout out to hers, you should definitely go check it out. 

When I see the dodge/burn notes on old film prints it‚Äôs a reminder that the art and intention of the shot doesn‚Äôt end until it‚Äôs delivered. I imagine some people would rather enjoy the magic without seeing how the sausage is made but I LOVE editing and always have.

I came up in this industry at a time where there was this odd mystique and elitism that I thankfully avoided, but I saw it discourage SO many people. And there was a tension because my income was also tied to education regarding editing and presets, and carving out a brand that was uniquely my voice. I‚Äôd much rather contribute to the shared pool of liberating knowledge so that the beautiful thing you were meant to do is not trapped behind something as dull as tone curves and split toning. 

The anchors of journalistic integrity are different than those for eliciting emotion. But you are also free to, and encouraged to, be unashamed about what does and doesn‚Äôt land with your creative preference. Just don‚Äôt make that the primary thing about your engagements with people on the internet. 

As always if you have questions about my process, whether it be gear, software, how I think about what I do, or anything else I‚Äôd so much rather communicate than get a ‚Äòlike‚Äô.

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar.

The history of sugar is bitter by dark moments of our human ego and desires for control.

For thousands of years, this sweetness was cultivated from the grass known as sugarcane, moving from Oceania by trade.

In colder climates of Europe where sugarcane would not grow, the demand for sugar during a time when such delights were rare, and spreading Colonization, the spice wars began in the 15th century for flavor-filled items like nutmeg, cinnamon, and yes, sugar. By the 18th century, most sugar was obtained from the West Indies.

During the Napoleonic Wars, sugar supplies were cut off by the English blockade of continental Europe.

To make up for this loss, Napoleon Bonaparte encouraged the growing of beets‚Ä¶in the 17th century, a German chemist discovered white and red beetroot contained sucrose, able to extract sugar.

After gaining a presence in France, the introduction of sugar beet production in the United States was first established, a short drive from where I live to North Hampton, MA‚Äîby 1883, ceasing operation.

It wasn‚Äôt until seeds arrived in North Dakota from Michigan in the late 1800s that sugar from beets became viable. With heavy labor done by German and Russian immigrants who moved to North Dakota for jobs, the surrounding areas of Fargo became the epicenter of sugar production in the United States.

In 1899, American Crystal Sugar was founded, and so began the most significant crop production of sugar beets in North America, along the Red River Valley in North Dakota.

From the @NatGeo story, The Culture of Sugar, which was never published (read why in the caption in my first post of this story), sharing with you the mesmerizing movement of how nearly all white processed sugar at American Crystal Sugar is produced for US consumption.

To understand the enormity of our desire for sweetness, the images inside the storage silo represent 35 million tonnes, or the equivalent of 7 million 2.3 kg (5 lb) bags of sugar.

A short film is in this album on the mysterious machines that create this sugar desire.

She got it on the first night of the storm so we‚Äôve kept her inside since then and it‚Äôs healing up nicely. (It‚Äôs Bebe, which is the same chicken who survived a raccoon attack this past summer. I've always had a fascination with the underground world. At first, I was obsessed with being one of the few people who could go into a cave. As my career progressed what caves preserve began to be more important. The underground world can act as a time capsule holding artwork made by people long before us. Those ancient artists are sending us messages from the past. My friend @dustign calls them "love notes in a bottle" from our ancestors. 
Those artists in the past are speaking to us if we let them. They are not just telling us who they were, they are telling us who we all are.

image 2) The Conoly Hole, TN, USA
image 3) Panel of the Four Horses, Chauvet Pont d'Arc, France
image 4) Unnamed Cave, AL, USA
image 5) Manitou Cave, AL, USA
image 6) Cave of La Pasiega, Spain

Thanks to @nasa astronaut @loralohara who I met today in space (via zoom), I got to look down at our amazing blue planet from the international space station, cruising amidst the cosmic ocean above us. 

Astronaut O‚ÄôHara, five months into a six month mission,  shared many insights about the fragility of our world, how borders vanish and natural systems connect, what life in zero gravity is like, the properties of water (droplets float), how planetary politics stay behind and much, much more. 
It blew my mind. 

The second image by @loralohara shows the entire Grand Canyon in all its eroded wonders in one single frame. It amazes me to think that it took me 71 days on foot to walk the length of that natural wonder, but the space station crosses it in seconds. 

Thanks again O‚ÄôHara and NASA for reminding us all the wonders we have not just in space, but right on our one shared home.

Picasso, a name synonymous with 20th-century art, stands tall in the annals of history. 

In 1913, it was rumored that a Parisian police officer, with a deep-seated animosity for modern art, accused Picasso of stealing the illustrious Mona Lisa. 

Years later, stories circulated about Picasso‚Äôs unique way of settling his restaurant tabs, often with a swift signature or a rapid sketch, prompting his quip, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm buying a meal, not the whole restaurant.‚Äù 

In a further twist, when a fan approached him in Paris for a simple doodle, Picasso humorously responded, ‚ÄúThat will be 30,000‚Äù, to the fan‚Äôs astonishment, explaining, ‚Äúthat took a lifetime.‚Äù

Indeed, Picasso‚Äôs life and art remain intertwined, shaping him into the iconic artist we know today.

A hippo in a typical threat display towards a rival in Phinda, South Africa. Hippos are known to be a bit grumpy, but if you read their behavior and play your cards right it always works really well. Hippos move with great ease in water, ‚Äùswimming‚Äù by kicking their hind feet or simply walking on the bottom. They are well-adapted to an aquatic lifestyle, with small ears, eyes and nostrils set at the top of the head. Their senses are super keen even when submerged in water. By closing its ears and nostrils, the adult can stay under water for as long as six minutes. It‚Äôs no secret that hippos love water, which is why the Greeks named them the ‚Äùriver horse.‚Äù Hippos can spend more than 16 hours a day submerged in rivers and lakes to keep their massive bodies cool under the hot African sun. The black market‚Äôs insatiable demand for ivory has turned poachers‚Äô attention away from well-protected elephants to more vulnerable hippos! 
Don‚Äôt buy exotic animal souvenirs!!

A recent article in The Economist reported on the issue of stray cows in India and how the right‚Äôs pro-cow policies are doing little to protect the sacred animals. I‚Äôve traveled to India over 10 times on assignment and have seen with my own eyes the way cows are a part of daily life. I‚Äôve always been fascinated by the special position cows have in Hindu society. At first I thought it was unusual, but over the years and many visits I‚Äôve come to not only appreciate the beliefs around a cow‚Äôs sacredness, but also understand that virtually every part of a cow, from their feces, meat, bones, skin, urine, etc, has a value. Whether it‚Äôs using their feces for fuel or building your home, to their skin for clothing and protection, it‚Äôs incredible what overall value, at least from a human‚Äôs perspective of dominion over the natural world, represents. No wonder cows are considered sacred. ‚Å£
‚Å£
But I‚Äôve also seen the downside of this reverence, where cows are left to wander and get sick and literally die on the streets. The ruling conservative party, BJP, has passed several ‚Äúpro-cow‚Äù policies like a ban on cow slaughter, but that has only led to the proliferation of stray cows, now numbering over 5 million. 

Abandoned, they often feed on plastic bags and other garbage, and can cause car crashes and destroy crops. One thing is certain ‚Äì the current situation is untenable and more must be done to protect India‚Äôs stray cows.‚Å£
‚Å£

This month marks 20 years since one of the most impactful moments of my life when a shark took my arm while on a surfing off the coast of Kauai, my birth place. Many people could look at the incident back in 2003 as a major setback for me, but God had so much in store for the future! ü§ôüèº

It‚Äôs absolutely wild to think how my life started and where it is now and all the amazing yet challenging things in between. I didn‚Äôt wake up in the hospital thinking I was invincible and was gonna get back to surfing. After getting a hint of inspiration,¬†¬†I had to dream it up, flip my mindset and be willing to do what I had not seen anyone else do.¬†¬†This was a challenge to live in faith. And I am so glad I was willing to try and give it my best shot! üôèüèº Now I get to surf with my two eldest sons Tobias and Wesley and my hubby! I get to enjoy these sweet moments with my newborn daughter. There is so much to be grateful for, and these past 20 years have been filled with incredible moments and huge overcoming seasons. üíõ

When you have your ‚ÄúShark Attack‚Äù moments in life. I hope you‚Äôre willing to try, and give life your best shot! You too CAN OVERCOME!
