PILATES FOR RUNNERS üëü If you‚Äôre a runner, sprinter, or even walker, you should be doing this!

Building strength in the glutes, stability in the hips & maintaining active feet is so important for efficient & injury free leg driven km‚Äôs (or miles!) üèÉüèΩ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüí®

I‚Äôve sped these videos up a little bit so remember to do each exercise slowly and with purpose!

TRY BEFORE RUNNING:
1-3 rounds depending how much time you have (the more often you do these, the better results you will get üí™üèº)

‚ñ™Ô∏è1. CLAM SEQUENCE
x10 each side

- do all 3 exercises in a row, making sure you don‚Äôt collapse in the bottom ribcage between each exercise.
- keep the hips still (like there are in concrete) 

üí•WORKS: Glute med & min - important for good lower body gait & hip stability

‚ñ™Ô∏è 2. SL TUCK CIRCLES
x10 each side

- keep belly button pulled in as you hold hips high & aim to keep hips still.

üí•WORKS: Glute max, med & min / hip flexors / abs - helps build hip stability during leg movement

‚ñ™Ô∏è3. SL EXTENDED RDL
x10 each side

- standing leg always has a slight bend
- fold at the hips & keep spine long (sit into standing leg a bit deeper)

üí•WORKS: Glute max, med & min, quads, hip flexor - improves balance, hip stability & foot strength

‚ñ™Ô∏è4. HIP HIKES
x10 each side

- move slowly & through full range on every rep (full up - full down)

üí•WORKS: Glute med & min / obliques - improves hip stability & lower body gait

‚ñ™Ô∏è5. FOOT SEQUENCE
x10 each side

Heel-Toe
- as you lean back pick up all 10 toes. Spread them as wide as you can as you roll foot forward then rise to toes.

Outdide-Inside
- slight bend in the knees & aim to find edges of your feet while spreading toes.

üí•WORKS: Calves / Smaller foot muscles - important for good foot biomechanics and strength (our feet become weak as we are constantly in shoes!)

Let me know if you‚Äôre a runner and what you think of these exercises! ‚ò∫Ô∏è #runningexercises #pilatesforrunners #runningrehab

In the past 10 years since starting Modern Macram√©, I have traveled the world teaching plant and wall-hanging workshops. I always dreamed of traveling for work, and I was lucky to be welcomed to teach in Mexico City, Barcelona, Copenhagen, Kyoto, Berlin, London, Amsterdam, and many more places. I visited our rope supplier in Turkey. 

In 2018 wrote a book about macram√© that finally paid out the advance this week! Woot! (a new book idea is brewing!)
 

I toured the USA in a mini van with my friend Caitlin teaching over 50 workshops from coast to coast over 3 months to celebrate that book.

I worked with amazing women in the studio and across the world, my teammates and my students who taught me so much about how to lead, how to be kind, how to ask for what you need, and how to be human. I am still learning. You know who you are.

We as a company sold over $3 million worth of rope, classes, and other craft supplies.

One of the other projects I did in Yemen were these portraits of Yemenis that played into the assignment I was working on, along with people I met during wanderings around different cities. 

This project could be the indirect reason I was detailed when I came back to the US. 

The second image is a portrait of the leader (at the time) of Al Qaeda‚Äôs political wing in Yemen.  He really liked the image and asked if I could send it to him. We used the old ‚Äúbump‚Äù iPhone app to exchange the image. And I‚Äôm pretty sure my phone was compromised from there on out. 

To make matters worse - we were meeting in a large cafe for safety - the next interview subject came in to meet the writer and I a bit early. The third image is a portrait of the last Rabbi in Yemen. Obviously the head of Al Qaeda and the Rabbi kept their affiliations on the DL - so neither knew who each one was. They actually exchanged pleasant greetings and traded places - as the rabbi stayed for an interview and portrait.

The fourth image is a former Guantanamo prisoner who was returned to Yemen after serving a few years in the prison and found either not guilty or not worth US efforts to interrogate him. He was unemployed and trying to figure out how to continue a life cut short. 

#portrait #photojournalism #reportage #onassignment #documentary #yemen #tintype

Excited to be launching this fellowship today, which I will be directing via @amplifierart! ‚ÄúAs threats to our democracy continue to evolve, so must we!¬† In the spirit of that evolution, we are excited to announce the launch of the Amplifier Democracy Fellowship!¬† Link in header!¬† Returning to our roots in photojournalism and community storytelling, we are merging our extensive networks in editorial journalism with insights from museum and art institution advisors, and building on a foundation of advising from leaders in nonprofits dedicated to safeguarding voting rights and other foundational elements of democracy.¬† With the support of this incredible team, we are committing to working with at least three photographers and photo-based artists in 2024.¬† Each fellow will be awarded $20,000 for the year.¬† With your support (via our print sales) we aim to expand this fellowship to launch additional rapid response grants and assignments throughout the year, showcasing work across new platforms, major media networks, and through our tried and true public interventions.

We are not here to merely observe democracy‚Äôs trials from the sidelines, but to engage deeply, to utilize our art to reinforce and protect the pillars of our democracy from decay and outright attack. Back in the days, the most powerful AMG V8 series engine of all time, the most expressive design, the most elaborate aerodynamics, the most intelligent material mix, the most distinctive driving dynamics: For the new Mercedes-AMG GT Black Series (combined fuel consumption 12.8 l/100 km, combined CO2 emissions 292 g/km)[1], the Affalterbach designers have pulled out all the stops when it comes to the art of vehicle design.

The super sports car perfectly embodies the brand‚Äôs rich tradition in motorsport, as well its many years of expertise in developing complete vehicles which impress in every respect. The result is an output of 537 kW (730 hp) from a V8 engine with a ‚Äöflat‚Äò crankshaft, combined with active aerodynamics and a design which stems directly from the current AMG GT3 racing car.

Different designs of V8 engines.

The design of a V8 engine gives designers plenty of room to play with in one key element: the crank arrangement on the crankshaft.
The result is the most powerful V8 series engine from Mercedes-AMG.

The GT Black Series engine may be based on the AMG 4.0-litre V8 biturbo engine with dry sump lubrication, but it has been given the new internal code M178 LS2 due to the numerous modifications. It achieves 730hp at 6700-6900 rpm and delivers a maximum torque of 800Nm at 2000-6000 rpm. New camshafts and exhaust manifolds are adapted to the new firing order and further improve the gas cycle.

Both twin scroll exhaust turbochargers are mounted in anti-friction bearings, as in the top-of-the-range four-door AMG GT CoupeÃÅ, which optimises their throttle response even further. However, in the Black Series, the turbochargers have been given a larger compressor wheel, meaning that both can deliver a total of 1100 kg air per hour.

Jump through, straight legs sit down. This is a phrase that you will hear over and over again and every single Ashtanga Yoga class. If you keep practicing, you may even hear this phrase in your dreams.

Learning to jump through holds so much information about inversions, strength, mental, focus, and surrender. You can‚Äôt rush the process of building the foundational strength in order to learn the lesson of jumping through. You can, however, focus on the step-by-step technique that will eventually lead you there. 

I remember when I first started practicing how frustrating it was that I couldn‚Äôt do this movement. Now, more than 20 years later, I still think there are many ways to refine the movement and get stronger. What‚Äôs important to me is not the performative aspect, but the connection of breath, awareness and mental focus. This is the essence of the flow that happens when our mind and body are completely harmonized.

Now I‚Äôm missing hearing my teacher tell us all to jump through as I unroll my mat on my own.

Silent nursery inside the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone. On the day the Nuclear Power Plant‚Äôs reactor #4 blew up, children oblivious to the nuclear accident played in this kindergarten of the reactor‚Äôs company town, Pripyat. The following day they were evacuated and had to leave everything behind ‚Äì even their treasured dolls and toys.

I have been given the rare opportunity to return to the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone and reactor #4 itself to document the highly contaminated areas beneath the New Safe Confinement and meet with victims, liquidators, and the few remaining returnees who are still living in the Zone. 

As traditional media outlets lack the necessary funds to support long-term reporting, I have once again turned to the Kickstarter community, colleagues, friends, and followers for assistance in this endeavor.

Part of my upcoming story on Zoroastrianism, the oldest monotheistic religion in the world, for @natgeo. Mehernosh, a pallbearer - the person in charge of carrying the dead body at a funeral - walks away from one of the two functioning towers of silence in Karachi.
A tower of silence, known as dakhma, is a circular structure built by Zoroastrians for excarnation - that means the exposure of human corpses to the elements for decomposition - in order to avoid contamination of the soil and other natural elements by the decomposing dead bodies. Carrion birds, usually vultures (though no longer in Karachi‚Ä¶) and other scavengers, consume the flesh. Skeletal remains are gathered into a central pit where further weathering and continued breakdown occurs. In this dakhma, reflective mirrors have been fitted inside the tower of silence to increase the heat and help the body decomposing faster.
Karachi, a city of 20 millions, has 800 Zoroastrians known as Parsees, 70% of them are above the age of 70 years old. #zoroastrianism #zoroastrian #towerofsilence #towersofsilence #parsi #parsee

It‚Äôs that kind of day where the clouds hang low on the horizon and the chance of sun is less likely than finding a pair of socks after they have entered the washing machine. The sky is a giant light box, and if I was in my studio today it would‚Äôve given me that soft milky light that I so often yearn for when creating my stillifes. There‚Äôs something about a bit of gentle light descending on a little set up of flowers or a handful of fruit from the local market. I remember this day well, getting up early and walking through a sleepy southern town in Italy to the food market. I filled my basket and returned back to where we were staying eager to begin creating. All I needed was a sliver of light descending over the scene like the caress of a feather, and so I cracked the big old oak door to a room without any windows, and let my stillife be illuminated by that slight ray of warm Italian light. There‚Äôs magic in every type of light, it‚Äôs all about using it to your advantage and learn to see what it can help create for you. Harsh contrasty midday sunshine holds just as much magic in it as a sliver of soft lighting on a cloudy day. It‚Äôs all about working with what you‚Äôve got and all my stillifes are created in very different light situations and locations, from caves in the south of Italy, to wonky old sheds with no window in the English countryside, to my sitting room bookshelves and on top of the nightstand in my cottage bedroom. A stormy day can offer up such wild and beautiful light, but so can a summers day at noon when the sun is in zenith. On my recent photography workshop in Florence we began the first day with the pursuit of light, learning to discover and recognise the power of natural light throughout the city, from artists studios, to alleyways, big old palazzo door openings and the incredible light reflecting off of the river Arno on a sunny day and big marble sculptures and surfaces. Light is truly where it all begins and ends for me in photography, and the more you hone your eye, the more you begin to see opportunities around every bend, like spotting your favourite colour everywhere. You can view my limited edition stillifes for sale on my website. xx

When someone asks me for an easy, healthy breakfast idea, this overnight oats recipe is the first thing I suggest. My base recipe is so simple to make and the flavor combinations are endlessly customizable (pb&j is always a winner!) üçì

Here‚Äôs how I do it:

* ¬Ω cup whole rolled oats
* 1 tablespoon chia seeds
* ¬Ω teaspoon maple syrup, plus more for serving
* Pinch of sea salt
* ¬º cup whole milk Greek yogurt, optional
* ‚Öî cup unsweetened almond milk
* Chia Jam
* Peanut butter
* Chopped strawberries
* Raspberries
* Chopped peanuts

In a Mason jar or other lidded jar, place the oats, chia seeds, maple syrup, salt, and Greek yogurt, if using. Add the almond milk and stir until the mixture is well combined and there are no clumps of chia seeds at the bottom of the jar. Cover and refrigerate overnight, or for up to 5 days.

In the morning, top with chia jam, peanut butter, chopped strawberries, raspberries, and chopped peanuts.‚Ä®

Lately I‚Äôve been meeting a lot of ‚Äúlost‚Äù people that seem to suffer from a crisis of confidence. I‚Äôm trying to help where I can. You don‚Äôt always have to understand the path forward. It‚Äôs OK to be lost at times. Crisis begets growth. In fact, some research shows that crisis is one of the few things that can really change us after age 25. If you‚Äôre feeling this way, just know that things can change in a moment ‚Äî a chance occurrence can change your life forever. In the meantime, fill your brain with good ideas, follow the signs that life is sending to you, be open to what‚Äôs possible. If you‚Äôre doing OK in life right now, give your smile and empathy to strangers and friends. We never know what someone is going through.  What does all this have to do with this photo? Happy Valentine‚Äôs Day! ‚ù§Ô∏è When resting, lions socialize through a number of behaviours. The most common peaceful tactile gestures are social licking and head rubbing which, for example can be compared with grooming in primates (or human stroking, cuddling, hugging etc). Social licking among lions often occurs in tandem with sometimes drawn out head rubbings. It‚Äôs generally mutual and the recipient clearly express pleasure. The head and neck are the most common parts of the body licked, which may have arisen out of utility, as a lion cannot lick these areas individually. Head rubbing ‚Äì nuzzling one‚Äôs forehead, nose and neck against another lion, is a form of greeting and I often see it after an animal has been apart from the pride, or after a fight or confrontation. In general males tend to rub other males, while cubs and females normally rub females. I took this picture in Thanda, South Africa. #protectbiodiversity #thanda #southafrica #nuzzle #africa #lion #science #happyvalentinesday #mattiasklum #savebigcats @mattiasklumcollection @thephotosociety @natgeo  @mattiasklumofficial

I was surprised how many people responded to what I wrote yesterday and glad to know people found comfort in my thoughts. üôè Often this feeling of being ‚Äúlost‚Äù comes from a larger cultural context. I just got back from Bhutan, a place where life feels integrated, whole, directed. About 7 years ago, I chose to live in multiple places around the world; I consider myself a member of various communities. The differences are striking. One of my favorite homes is Hawaii. üèùTomorrow I‚Äôm going there.ü§ôPart of why I love Hawaii and why it feels like home to me is similar to the feeling I get in Bhutan. There‚Äôs an attitude of calm in Hawaii. You see it in everything, from the speed of traffic, to the gait with which people walk. üë£In part, it‚Äôs island life, but it runs deeper than geography. It‚Äôs cultural and philosophical. When your community is strong, your purpose in life feels more secure. üíïThe state of Hawaii is ranked lowest in the US for depression. üòÄIt‚Äôs fifth lowest for separation and divorce. üë®‚Äçüë©‚Äçüëß‚Äçüë¶Is this all because of sunny weather and beautiful beaches? I don‚Äôt think so. It helps, but that‚Äôs not the whole story. There‚Äôs a saying or hashtag you may have seen on Instagram #luckywelivehawaii To me, that simple idea reflects pride, gratitude, and wisdom, all in one concept: pride in heritage and traditions, gratitude for that heritage to exist and continue, and wisdom of those living in Hawaii to recognize the uniqueness that their heritage does exist and continue. üåèüòéWhen you exist in a community like that, you‚Äôre less likely to suffer as an individual. If you‚Äôre struggling on a personal level, sometimes the answer may lie outside yourself‚Äîin a community that‚Äôs waiting for you. Aloha :) üèÑ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

Ilyinsty, Ukraine, 2005. None of the nearly 400 elderly living in the Exclusion Zone have easy access to medical treatment. To ensure basic health care, teams of doctors from the Chernobyl hospital make their rounds to different villages about once every month.

I just returned from Zurich, where I attended the opening of the OPEN YOUR EYES Photo Festival. Running until October 15, 2023, OPEN YOUR EYES presents a festival of creative photography to the public in Zurich ‚Äì as a plea for understanding the UN‚Äôs 17 Sustainable Development Goals. The photographs are exhibited in the streets, squares, and parks of Zurich to break the boundaries with viewers and involve them in the process of reflecting on these works, which have been created around the globe and show the social, political, scientific, and cultural diversity of our world from a different perspective.

The image above is part of my Chernobyl exhibition in Zurich. I‚Äôm happy to say that this year, The Photo Society was a partner of OPEN YOUR EYES and nearly 50% of the of all exhibits at the festival are by friends of mine from @ThePhotoSociety. Follow @fotofestivalzuerich to see more photos from all the exhibits.

In 2007 I was hired by @timberland to do a series of ads where they wanted a sense of motion conveyed, without using motion blur. I pitched them on using light streaks to show motion paths, by strapping headlamps to hands and wrists of athletes. This one here was with my friend @joekinder climbing on a bridge near Manitou Springs, CO. To capture this frame we determined the end point of the frame where my flash would fire and freeze the action, which is essentially what frame 3 is. Joe started at the base, and climbed to that point with headlamps on wrists and feet, while I left the shutter open, firing the flash once he hit our established end point. The total exposure time was 94 seconds, leaving behind his light path in a fun way, all done entirely in camera.

18 grey/Lebanese zucchini, washed & cored
1 tbsp oil
1 small onion, diced
500g beef mince
1 1/2 tsp baharat 
1 tsp pomegranate molasses 
1 tbsp pine nuts 
Salt & pepper

Heat olive oil in a fry pan. Add pine nuts and toast until they just turn a golden brown. Add the onion & saut√© until soft. Add the mince, stir to brown and remove large lumps of meat. Add baharat, molasses & salt/pepper to taste. Stir through. Return pine nuts to pan. Combine well. Set aside to cool. 

·¥¢·¥ú·¥Ñ·¥Ñ ú…™…¥…™ 
Once stuffing has cooled, use fingers to gently stuff each zucchini. 

In a large fry pan, melt 2 tbsp ghee. Fry the zucchini, turning frequently, in batches until they just change colour. Return all the zucchini to pan & cover with just enough water. Bring to a gentle boil & leave to simmer for 20 min. (Place a heat proof plate on the zucchini to keep them submerged). 

At 20 min the zucchini should have softened. Remove from water & set aside. Do not discard the cooking water. Strain it & set aside. (There should be about 2 cups of liquid, if less top it up with more water to make 2 cups).

In a small frypan, melt the ghee or butter. Add the crushed garlic and mint. Cook stirring for two minutes. Set aside.

Shakespeare, the name synonymous with English literature, was not always held in such high regard. 

In fact, for a century and a half after his death, he was merely another playwright among many. 

It was only as the 19th century dawned, and his works began to be studied with fervor, that doubts about the real authorship came to light. 

With no existing documents penned by Shakespeare himself, save for six inconsistently spelled and poorly written signatures, the mystery deepens. 

Thus, the question of Shakespeare‚Äôs authorship remains, a tantalizing enigma in the world of literature.

BACKGROUND for the conflict:‚Å†
Since the 1990s, The Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) has experienced a decades-long war that has roots in a struggle for power. The complex conflict followed the end of colonialism and the eruption of independence in DRC in the 1960s. Mining has played a large role in supplying finance to several rebel groups operating in DRC, causing gross damage, millions of deaths, and displacements of the people living here.‚Å†

Please DONATE to CKI: ‚Å†
Congo Kids Initiative (CKI) is specifically for children who have lost their parents and communities to the conflict. St. Kizito is a facility located in the town of Bunia at the site of some of the most extreme violence. They work with local partners that determine targets of how these children can be provided with the most loving, sustainable, and nurturing environment. Donations can help CKI to provide early-childhood and primary education, medical care, and resources for the children to reintegrate with family and society to live more independent lives long-term. ‚Å†

I've always been in awe of the sheer power and presence of elephants. While spending time with these giants you learn to appreciate the delicate application of that immense strength. A carefully directed blast of water from a trunk provides relief from the scorching African sun, while pillar-like legs are used to dig into the sand when rivers run dry. Their movements are purposeful and intricate fuelled by an intelligence and social cohesion that we are yet to fully understand. Although, we don't speak their language and can only deduce the motivations for their behaviour, we can respect and admire their sentience. And do everything we can to protect them.‚Å£‚Å£

Eye to Eye. 

It‚Äôs tough to watch any animal die. Our human instinct is to look away and feel a sense of shame/guilt for even wanting the hunt to happen in the first place. It‚Äôs a normal and perfectly fine reaction. But life in the Maasai Mara is not easy, and lions must kill to survive. We‚Äôve lost over 90% of the lion population in the last 50+ years. Lions are in serious trouble, and I can‚Äôt imagine a world in which we can‚Äôt see them in the wild. So I try to bear witness, without wishing a kill to happen but also not looking away when it does.

On this particular morning, these two male lions ambushed a rather large herd of buffalo, and managed to separate this one from the group. It was over rather quickly, as these two brothers are expert hunters and together there‚Äôs not much that they can‚Äôt take down. That‚Äôs more than I can say for other kills I‚Äôve witnessed. 

Such is the tug and pull (figuratively, and in this case, quite literally too) of life on the Mara. #kenya #safari
